  <section id="faqs" class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">FAQs: D7 Visa Insurance</h2>

    <div class="space-y-4">
      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Which insurance do Portuguese consulates actually accept for D7 visas?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">
          Cigna Global, Bupa Global, and Allianz Care are all routinely accepted. Portuguese consulates require proof of comprehensive health coverage valid in Portugal—these three providers meet that requirement. Request a coverage letter in English or Portuguese from your insurer for your application. Travel insurance or short-term policies are typically NOT accepted; you need annual comprehensive health insurance.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How do pre-existing conditions affect my application?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">
          All three providers conduct medical underwriting. Well-controlled conditions (managed diabetes, hypertension, high cholesterol) typically result in either premium loadings or waiting periods rather than outright rejection. Apply to all three and compare the specific terms offered. Allianz is often most flexible with loadings vs. exclusions. Be completely honest in your application—non-disclosure can void your policy when you need it most.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Should I keep international insurance after qualifying for SNS?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">
          Most D7 holders maintain international insurance alongside SNS eligibility. SNS provides free public healthcare but has wait times for non-urgent care and limited English availability. Private insurance gives you faster access, English-speaking doctors, private rooms, and coverage during travel. Many retirees use SNS for prescriptions and routine care while keeping international insurance for serious illness and convenience.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What if I already have travel insurance?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">
          Travel insurance doesn't satisfy D7 visa requirements. Portuguese immigration requires comprehensive annual health insurance, not travel insurance with limited coverage periods and exclusions for ongoing conditions. Travel insurance is designed for short trips, not residence. You'll need proper international health insurance for your D7 application.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I switch providers after getting my visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">
          Yes, you can switch at any renewal period. However, switching triggers new medical underwriting with the new provider. Any conditions that developed while on your previous policy may be treated as pre-existing by the new insurer. If you've developed health issues, staying with your current provider (who must continue covering you) is often wiser than switching and risking exclusions.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What happens when I turn 75 or 80?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">
          All three providers offer lifetime coverage once you're enrolled—they won't drop you due to age. However, premiums increase significantly with age, and by 75-80, annual costs may exceed €10,000-15,000. Many retirees reduce coverage at advanced ages, increase deductibles, or rely more on SNS. The important thing is enrolling while you're younger; qualifying for new coverage becomes much harder after 74.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
